      • read

        public <I extends XmlObjectModelling> int read(I[] array)
                                        throws java.io.IOException,
                                               XmlInvalidLtException
        Reads some number of objects from the reader and stores them into the buffer array. The number of objects actually read is returned as an integer. This method blocks until all array objects is available, end of stream is detected, or an exception is thrown.

        If the length of array is zero, then no objects are read and 0 is returned; otherwise, there is an attempt to read at least one object. If no object is available because the stream is at the end, the value -1 is returned.

        Parameters:
        array - into which object is read
        Returns:
        the total number of objects read into the array, or -1 if there is no more objects because the end of the reader has been reached
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException - If an I/O error occurs
        XmlInvalidLtException - If is reading a corrupted XML
        java.lang.NullPointerException - If array is null

      • read

        public <I extends XmlObjectModelling> int read(I[] array,
                                               int off,
                                               int len)
                                        throws java.io.IOException,
                                               XmlInvalidLtException
        Reads up to len objects from the reader and stores them into the buffer array. The number of objects actually read is returned as an integer.This method blocks until objects are available, end of stream is detected, or an exception is thrown.

        If len is zero, then no objects are read and 0 is returned; otherwise, there is an attempt to read at least one object. If no object is available because the stream is at the end, the value -1 is returned.

        The first object read is stored into element array[off], the next one into array[off+1], and so on. The number of objects read is, at most, equal to len.

        In every case, elements array[0] through array[off] and elements array[off+len] through array[b.length-1] are unaffected.

        Parameters:
        array - into which object is read
        off - the start offset in array at which the object is written
        len - the maximum number of objects to read
        Returns:
        the total number of objects read into the array, or -1 if there is no more objects because the end of the reader has been reached
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException - If an I/O error occurs
        XmlInvalidLtException - If is reading a corrupted XML
        java.lang.NullPointerException - If array is null
        java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException - If off is negative, len is negative, or len is greater than b.length - off

      • read

        public <I extends XmlObjectModelling> java.util.List<I> read(java.lang.Class<I> interfaceClass,
                                                             int len)
                                                      throws java.io.IOException,
                                                             XmlInvalidLtException
        Reads all the objects of type interfaceClass till len or the end of reader.

        If len is zero, then no objects are read and an empty list is returned; otherwise, there is an attempt to read at least one object. If no object is available because the reader is at the end, the value null is returned.

        Parameters:
        interfaceClass - type of object to be ridden
        len - max number of objects to read
        Returns:
        list of all the ridden objects, or null if there is no more objects because the end of the reader has been reached
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException - If an I/O error occurs
        XmlInvalidLtException - If is reading a corrupted XML
        java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException - If len is negative

      • skip

        public long skip(long n)
          throws java.io.IOException,
                 XmlInvalidLtException
        Skips over and discards n objects from this reader. The skip method may, for a variety of reasons, end up skipping over some smaller number of objects, possibly 0. This may result from any of a number of conditions; reaching end of reader before n objects have been skipped is only one possibility. The actual number of objects skipped is returned. If n is negative, the skip method always returns 0, and no objects are skipped.
        Parameters:
        n - the number of objects to be skipped
        Returns:
        the actual number of bytes skipped
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException - If an I/O error occurs
        XmlInvalidLtException - If is reading a corrupted XML
